// C2: Acting Components
instance PermanentMagnetSynchronousMotor : DTDFVocab:ActingComponent [
    base:desc "Primary actuator in the MABI MAX 100 robot's first axis, operating within a maximum working range of [-90°, 90°] and achieving a peak speed of 75°/s. Governed by closed-loop control system with defined operational constraints."
]

instance GearboxAssembly : DTDFVocab:ActingComponent [
    base:desc "Mechanical component integrated with the PermanentMagnetSynchronousMotor to transmit torque and motion, forming part of the robot's kinematic chain for precision manufacturing tasks."
]

// C3: Physical sensing components
instance PrimaryPositionEncoder : DTDFVocab:SensingComponent [
    base:desc "High-precision position encoder per drive providing real-time positional feedback for system monitoring and control, with distributed spatial coverage across the robot's joints."
    DTDFVocab:producedData PrimaryPositionData
]

instance SecondaryPositionEncoder : DTDFVocab:SensingComponent [
    base:desc "Secondary high-precision position encoder per drive providing redundant real-time positional feedback for system monitoring and control, ensuring data consistency."
    DTDFVocab:producedData SecondaryPositionData
]

// C4: Physical-to-virtual interaction
instance PrimaryPositionData : DTDFVocab:DataTransmitted [
    DTDFVocab:producedFrom PrimaryPositionEncoder
]

instance SecondaryPositionData : DTDFVocab:DataTransmitted [
    DTDFVocab:producedFrom SecondaryPositionEncoder
]

instance JointFrictionData : DTDFVocab:DataTransmitted [
    DTDFVocab:producedFrom PrimaryPositionEncoder
    base:desc "Aggregated contextual data traces derived from position encoders, processed to identify joint friction dynamics for kinematic modeling accuracy."
]

// C10: Models/Data
instance SysMLArchitectureModel : DTDFVocab:Model [
    base:desc "Structural model of the MABI MAX 100 robot's architecture using SysML, including components (motor, gearbox), interfaces, and interconnections as depicted in Fig. 3."
    DTDFVocab:inputTo SysMLSimulationEnabler
]

instance SimulinkKinematicModel : DTDFVocab:Model [
    base:desc "Behavioral simulation model of the robot's kinematic and dynamic behavior implemented in MathWorks MATLAB Simulink, enabling real-time or near-real-time simulation of movements and friction dynamics."
    DTDFVocab:inputTo SimulinkSimulationEnabler
]

instance PositionDataTrace : DTDFVocab:Data [
    base:desc "Aggregated and abstracted time-series data from position encoders, processed for performance monitoring and predictive maintenance analysis."
    DTDFVocab:fromData PrimaryPositionData, SecondaryPositionData
    DTDFVocab:inputTo DataAggregationEnabler
]

instance FrictionAnalysisData : DTDFVocab:Data [
    base:desc "Processed contextual traces focusing on joint friction identification, derived from position encoder data and used for model refinement."
    DTDFVocab:fromData JointFrictionData
    DTDFVocab:inputTo DataAggregationEnabler
]

// C11: Enablers
instance SysMLSimulationEnabler : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "SysML-based structural modeling tool enabling component-connector modeling and behavioral specifications for the robot's architecture."
    DTDFVocab:enables ArchitectureAnalysisService
]

instance SimulinkSimulationEnabler : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "MathWorks MATLAB Simulink simulation environment for dynamic analysis of the robot's kinematic and friction behavior."
    DTDFVocab:enables KinematicSimulationService
]

instance DataAggregationEnabler : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "Middleware/ETL pipeline for aggregating and abstracting heterogeneous sensor data traces into purpose-specific datasets for analysis."
    DTDFVocab:enables DataProcessingService
]

// C6: Services
instance ArchitectureAnalysisService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Service providing structural analysis and component-connector validation of the robot's architecture using SysML models."
    DTDFVocab:provides ArchitectureInsight
]

instance KinematicSimulationService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Service enabling real-time or near-real-time simulation of the robot's movements and friction dynamics using Simulink models."
    DTDFVocab:provides KinematicInsight
]

instance DataProcessingService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Service processing and abstracting contextual data traces to generate insights for manufacturing engineers and maintenance teams."
    DTDFVocab:provides FrictionAnalysisInsight
]

// C17: Insights/Actions
instance ArchitectureInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Structural validation insights derived from SysML architecture models, ensuring consistency between physical and digital representations."
]

instance KinematicInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Dynamic behavior insights from Simulink simulations, including movement accuracy and friction impact analysis."
]

instance FrictionAnalysisInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Predictive insights on joint friction dynamics derived from processed position encoder data, enabling model refinement for improved kinematic accuracy."
]

// C1: Environment
instance ManufacturingEnvironment : DTDFVocab:Environment [
    base:desc "Industrial manufacturing environment where the MABI MAX 100 robot operates, characterized by high-precision automation requirements."
    base:contains PermanentMagnetSynchronousMotor, GearboxAssembly, PrimaryPositionEncoder, SecondaryPositionEncoder
]

// C5: Component
instance MABIMax100Robot : DTDFVocab:Component [
    base:desc "Serial industrial robot designed for precision manufacturing tasks, featuring complex kinematic chains and sensor-instrumented feedback loops for state tracking."
    base:isContainedIn ManufacturingEnvironment
]

instance twinning_time_scale : DTDFVocab:TimeScale [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin system described in the provided documents does not explicitly detail synchronization frequencies, time scales for services, latency requirements, or temporal granularity needs. However, the context implies that **Model-Based Systems Engineering (MBSE)** methodologies (e.g., SysML, ADLs like AADL, or MontiArc) are used to model system behavior, which inherently requires **temporal alignment** between physical and digital components. For example, **SysML IBDs (Internal Block Diagrams)** and **state machines in SysML v1.7** or **MontiArc Automaton** may enforce discrete or continuous time modeling, depending on the simulation tools (e.g., **MathWorks Simulink** or other simulation methods [29, 30]) integrated with the digital twin. Latency and granularity would depend on the specific use case, but the documents suggest that **real-time or near-real-time synchronization** is implied for active components (e.g., digital twins acting as interpreters of data flows [33, 34]). No explicit time-scale metrics (e.g., Hz, ms, or sampling intervals) are provided in the text."
]

instance dt_constellation : DTDFVocab:Constellation [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin system’s orchestration is defined by **architecture description languages (ADLs)** such as **ACME, AADL, MontiArc**, and **SysML Internal Block Diagrams (IBDs)**, which model systems from a **component & connector perspective**, including interfaces, interconnections, and composition. Behavioral coordination is achieved through **state machines (SysML v1.7)** and **MontiArc Automaton**, while detailed behavior is integrated via **simulation tools (MathWorks Simulink)** or **general-purpose code (C++, Java)**. The system emphasizes **heterogeneous tool integration** to manage complexity, but does not explicitly detail **resource management** (e.g., priority scheduling, load balancing) or **system-wide coordination mechanisms** beyond the ADL/IBD frameworks. The architecture follows **modular, component-based patterns** with explicit separation of concerns (e.g., functional vs. physical layers)."
]

instance life_cycle_stages : DTDFVocab:EvolutionStage [
    base:desc "The lifecycle of a Digital Twin (DT) system is structured through **Model-Based Systems Engineering (MBSE)** methodologies, encompassing multiple abstraction layers: **requirements, functional architecture, logical architecture, and product/technical layers**. The transition between stages is managed via **architecture description languages (ADLs)** such as **SysML (Systems Modeling Language)**, **ACME, AADL (Architecture Analysis & Design Language), MontiArc**, or **SysML Internal Block Diagrams (IBDs)**, which define **component-connector perspectives** (e.g., interfaces, interconnections, and composition). Behavior modeling is further refined using **state machines in SysML v1.7** or **MontiArc Automaton**, while detailed simulations are integrated via tools like **MathWorks Simulink**, other simulation engines, or general-purpose programming languages (e.g., **C++ or Java**). Lifecycle governance involves **heterogeneous stakeholder integration** and **multi-tool interoperability**, ensuring alignment across **requirements, functional, logical, and physical models**. Transition management between phases adheres to structured methodologies like **RFLP (Requirements, Functions, Logics, Physics)**, **OOSEM (Object-Oriented Systems Engineering Methodology)**, **SPES (Systematic Process for Engineering Systems)**, or **SMArDT (Smart Digital Twin Methodology)** to maintain consistency and traceability across evolving DT representations."
]

instance fidelity_and_validity_considerations : DTDFVocab:FidelityConsideration [
    base:desc "
The Digital Twin’s **fidelity and validity** are constrained by its **passive data flow architecture**, where the digital shadow lacks autonomous feedback mechanisms to correct physical system deviations. Validation is implicitly tied to **simulating expected behavior** using integrated models (e.g., SysML, Simulink), but explicit **Verification and Validation (V&V) methodologies** (e.g., formal testing, uncertainty quantification, or error correction protocols) are not described. Uncertainty sources (e.g., sensor noise, model approximations) are not quantified, and **quality assurance processes** rely on the passive aggregation of data traces rather than active calibration. The system’s reliance on **one-way data flow** implies limitations in real-time error detection, though the robustness of behavioral models (e.g., state machines in SysML) may infer indirect validation through consistency checks against simulated outputs.
"
]

instance dt_technical_connection : DTDFVocab:TechnicalConnection [
    base:desc "The technical network infrastructure for the Digital Twin system’s digital shadow component is explicitly tied to **MQTT** as the communication protocol for streaming sensor time series from physical objects to the digital representation. The document does not provide details on network topology (e.g., star, mesh, or hierarchical), bandwidth requirements, latency specifications, or redundancy mechanisms. Security protocols for network communication are also not mentioned. While the document acknowledges the need for heterogeneous data integration in broader system engineering contexts, it does not elaborate on the underlying network architecture beyond the MQTT protocol for data transmission."
]

instance dt_hosting_deployment : DTDFVocab:Deployment [
    base:desc "The document does not specify the **deployment infrastructure** for Digital Twin systems. While it mentions the use of **modeling tools** (e.g., MathWorks Simulink, C++/Java) and **architecture description languages** (e.g., AADL, SysML), there is no mention of hosting platforms (cloud, edge, or on-premise), **computational/storage requirements**, **scalability mechanisms**, or **deployment models** (e.g., containerization, microservices). The document also does not reference specific technologies like Kubernetes, Docker, or cloud providers (AWS, Azure). The focus is on **modeling and abstraction** rather than deployment infrastructure."
]

instance horizontal_integration : DTDFVocab:HoriIntegration [
    base:desc "The document mentions **MQTT-based streaming** of sensor time series data as the primary mechanism for external data exchange, but does not specify broader **interoperability standards** (e.g., OPC UA, XML/JSON APIs) or **enterprise system integrations** (e.g., SCADA, MES, ERP). Horizontal integration is implicitly supported by the **MBSE toolchain** (SysML, Simulink, C++/Java), which enables cross-tool communication via **model exchanges** (e.g., SysML profiles) and **simulation interfaces**, though no explicit **ETL pipelines**, **API gateways**, or **mediator patterns** are described. Dependencies on external systems are limited to **sensor data ingestion** (MQTT) and **active processing components** (e.g., software interpreters for digital shadows), with no mention of broader ecosystem integration."
]

instance security_and_safety_considerations : DTDFVocab:SecuritySafety [
    base:desc "
The Digital Twin system referenced in the provided documents incorporates **safety-critical design principles** through the **safety cell** concept, which restricts the maximum working range of robotic assets (e.g., the MABI robotic arm) to predefined operational boundaries. This ensures physical safety by limiting motion to non-hazardous zones, as implied in the context of robotic manufacturing applications (Document [44]).

For data transmission, the system employs **MQTT (Message Queuing Telemetry Transport)** protocols (Document [52]) to stream sensor data from physical assets to the Digital Twin, enabling real-time monitoring and control. However, **no explicit mention of encryption (e.g., TLS), authentication mechanisms, or threat mitigation strategies** is provided in the documents. The system’s reliance on MQTT alone implies potential vulnerabilities unless additional security layers (e.g., access control or firewalls) are implemented externally, which are not detailed in the provided sources.

No references to **cybersecurity frameworks (e.g., ISO/IEC 62443)**, **RAMI 4.0 security layers**, or **safety-critical system certifications** (e.g., IEC 61508) are present in the documents. The **Asset Administration Shell (AAS)** (Documents [46], [47], [50]) is described as a standardized data model for digital assets but does not explicitly address security governance or privacy compliance in the provided excerpts."
]